## LEADER REPLICA
------------------

Har partition ka ek leader hota hai.

Producer jo bhi message publish karta hai, agar wo message kisi particular partition me map hota hai, to sabse pehle us Partition ke Leader Replica me store hota hai.

Baaki copies /replica followers hoti hain.

Leader partion
   |
   +----> Follower partition
   |
   +----> Follower partition


## FOLLOWER REPLICA
---------------------

Follower partitions continuously leader partition se data copy karti rehta hai.

Consumer jab bhi kisi partition se data read karega, to wo hamesha us partition ke leader replica se hi data read karega.

Maan lo:

Broker-1 crash ho gaya.

Aur Broker-1 par:

Partition-0 (Leader) present tha.


Kafka detect karega ki Leader unavailable ho gaya hai.

Kafka available ISR followers me se kisi ek ko new Leader Replica ke roop me promote kar dega. (Refer: ISR and Partition Leader Election)

Example:

Broker-3
 |
 Partition-0

Follower ---> Leader


- Ab going forward Producer aur Consumer dono naye Leader Replica se interact karenge.

- Agar koi naya message Partition-0 me map hota hai, to Producer us message ko Broker-3 par maujood Partition-0 ke Leader Replica me store karega.

- Similarly, Consumer bhi ab Partition-0 ka data Broker-3 par maujood naye Leader Replica se hi consume karega.


## IMPORTANT:
--------------

Yahan hum baar-baar bol rahe hain:

"Kafka detect karega"

Lekin actually Kafka ke andar ye kaam kaun karta hai?

Answer:

Kafka Controller

- Purane Kafka (ZooKeeper Mode) me cluster metadata ZooKeeper me maintain hota tha. 
  Kafka Controller isi metadata ka use karke cluster ko manage karta tha aur jab kisi Partition ka Leader unavailable ho jata tha, 
  to ISR (In-Sync Replicas) me se suitable Follower Replica ko naya Leader elect karta tha.

- Modern Kafka (KRaft Mode) me ZooKeeper remove ho chuka hai. Ab Kafka Controller khud cluster metadata maintain karta hai 
  aur Leader Replica unavailable hone par ISR (In-Sync Replicas) me se suitable Follower Replica ko naya Leader promote karta hai.


