10 : Consumer Group Coordinator
===================================

Har Consumer Group ke liye Kafka Cluster ka koi ek Broker automatically Group Coordinator ka role perform karta hai.
Ye Broker us Consumer Group se related coordination aur management ka kaam handle karta hai.

Example:

Suppose Kafka cluster mai 4 brokers hai namely Broker-1, Broker-2, Broker-3 and Broker-4

also assume Topic = Orders

and Orders topic has 3 Partitions:

Orders
|
|-Partition-0
|-Partition-1
|-Partition-2


Maan lo 3 consumers (say C1, C2 and C3) 'Orders' topic ko listen kar rahe hain aur teeno same consumer group se belong karte hain, say 'order-group'.

order-group:
|
|- Consumer-1
|- Consumer-2
|- Consumer-3


For instance 'order-group' ke liye bhi koi ek broker out of the avaialable 4 brokers in the clusters will act as the group cordinator
man lete hai 'order-group' consumer group ke like Broker-2 will act as group coordinator. i,e Ab 'order-group' se related sab management ka kaam ye broker karega.

------------------------------------------
Consumer Group Coordinator Kya Karta Hai?
------------------------------------------

## 1. CONSUMER JOIN KARWATA HAI
--------------------------------

Jab bhi koi naya Consumer kisi Consumer Group ko join karta hai, to us Consumer ko Group me register karne ka kaam Consumer Group Coordinator ka hota hai.
Kyunki Consumer Group ki composition change ho jaati hai (ek naya Consumer add ho gaya), isliye Rebalancing trigger hoti hai.
Rebalancing ke dauran Consumer Group Coordinator available Consumers aur Topic ke Partitions ke basis par Partition Assignment Strategy (Range, Round Robin, Sticky, Cooperative Sticky) 
ka use karke decide karta hai ki kaunsi Partition kis Consumer ko assign hogi.


##2. PARTITION ASSIGNMENT KARWATA HAI
-------------------------------------

Consumer Group ke andar kaunsa Consumer kis Partition ko consume karega, ye decide karne ka kaam Consumer Group Coordinator ka hota hai. Jab Rebalancing trigger hoti hai, 
to Group Coordinator configured Partition Assignment Strategy (Range, Round Robin, Sticky ya Cooperative Sticky) ka use karke available Consumers ke beech Partitions assign karta hai.

Is order-group ka group-coordinator (i.e Broker-2) partition assignment kuch aisa kar sakta hai :

Partition-0 -> Consumer-1
Partition-1 -> Consumer-2
Partition-2 -> Consumer-3


##3. HEARTBEATS RECEIVE KARTA HAI
-----------------------------------

Heartbeat ek chhota sa signal hota hai jo Consumer periodically Consumer Group Coordinator ko bhejta rehta hai.

Basically Consumer bol raha hota hai:

"Coordinator bhai, main zinda hoon."

Heartbeats ka purpose ye verify karna hota hai ki Consumer abhi bhi active hai ya nahi.


## AGAR HEARTBEAT BAND HO JAYE TO?

Consider the above example:

Ab maan lo:

Consumer-2 crash ho gaya.

To Consumer-2 se Heartbeats aana band ho jayengi.

Consumer Group Coordinator observe karega:

Heartbeat Missing
Heartbeat Missing
Heartbeat Missing

Agar configured timeout tak Heartbeat receive nahi hoti, to Coordinator Consumer-2 ko dead mark kar dega.

Assume:

Consumer-2 = DEAD


## FIR KYA HOGA?
------------------

Jaise hi Consumer-2 dead declare hota hai, Consumer Group Coordinator Rebalancing trigger karega.

Pehle Assignment:

Partition-0 -> Consumer-1
Partition-1 -> Consumer-2
Partition-2 -> Consumer-3

Rebalancing ke baad ek possible assignment:

Partition-0 -> Consumer-1
Partition-1 -> Consumer-3
Partition-2 -> Consumer-3

Ya koi aur valid assignment.

Yahi reason hai ki Heartbeats aur Rebalancing closely related concepts hain.

Heartbeats Consumer ki health monitor karti hain, aur Heartbeat fail hone par Rebalancing trigger ho sakti hai.

-------------------------------
## HEARTBEAT & SESSION TIMEOUT
-------------------------------

##1. SESSION.TIMEOUT.MS
--------------------------

Meaning:
    Defines how long the Consumer Group Coordinator should wait
    without receiving a heartbeat before considering the consumer dead.

Example:

    session.timeout.ms = 10000

Meaning:

    If no heartbeat is received for 10 seconds,
    Coordinator assumes:

        "Consumer is dead"

    and triggers a rebalance.


##2. HEARTBEAT.INTERVAL.MS
----------------------------

Meaning:
    Defines how frequently a consumer sends heartbeats
    to the Consumer Group Coordinator.

Example:

    heartbeat.interval.ms = 3000

Meaning:

    t = 0 sec   -> Heartbeat
    t = 3 sec   -> Heartbeat
    t = 6 sec   -> Heartbeat
    t = 9 sec   -> Heartbeat
    ...

Consumer is basically telling the coordinator:

    "I am alive."
    "I am alive."
    "I am alive."



## HOW HEARTBEAT.INTERVAL.MS  IS RELATED TO  SESSION.TIMEOUT.MS
----------------------------------------------------------------


Example:

    heartbeat.interval.ms = 3000
    session.timeout.ms    = 10000

Flow:

    t = 0 sec   -> Heartbeat
    t = 3 sec   -> Heartbeat
    t = 6 sec   -> Heartbeat

    Consumer crashes

    t = 9 sec   -> No heartbeat
    t = 12 sec  -> No heartbeat
    t = 15 sec  -> No heartbeat

Coordinator keeps waiting.

Once 10 seconds have passed since the last heartbeat
(i.e. since t = 6 sec), session timeout is exceeded.

Coordinator concludes:

    "Consumer is dead"

and triggers a rebalance.



## IMPORTANT RULE
------------------

Generally:

    heartbeat.interval.ms
            <
    session.timeout.ms

should always be true.

Correct Example:

    heartbeat.interval.ms = 3000
    session.timeout.ms    = 10000

Reason:
    Multiple heartbeat attempts can happen before
    the session timeout expires.

Incorrect Example:

    heartbeat.interval.ms = 15000
    session.timeout.ms    = 10000

Problem:

    Session timeout will be reached before
    the next heartbeat is sent.

Result:

    Coordinator may mark the consumer as dead
    even though it is actually running.


----------------------
## MAX POLL INTERVAL
----------------------

##1. MAX.POLL.INTERVAL.MS
---------------------------

Meaning:
    Defines the maximum time allowed between
    two consecutive poll() calls by a consumer.

    If the consumer does not call poll()
    within this configured time,
    Kafka assumes the consumer is stuck
    and removes it from the consumer group.

Example:

    max.poll.interval.ms = 300000

Meaning:

    Consumer must call poll() at least once
    every 5 minutes.


## WHY MAX.POLL.INTERVAL.MS  IS REQUIRED
-----------------------------------------

Consider:

    Consumer 
        |
        V
      poll()
        |
        v
    Message Processing Starts

Suppose processing takes:

    15 minutes

During this time:

    Heartbeats are still being sent

So from Coordinator's perspective:

    "Consumer is alive."

However Kafka now has another concern:

    "Is the consumer actually making progress?"

Because:

    It has not called poll() again
    for a very long time.

Kafka may assume:

    "Consumer is stuck"

    OR

    "Consumer is taking too long"



## WHAT HAPPENS WHEN  MAX.POLL.INTERVAL.MS  EXPIRES
------------------------------------------------------------

Example:

    max.poll.interval.ms = 5 minutes

Timeline:

    t = 0 min  -> poll()
    t = 1 min  -> Processing
    t = 2 min  -> Processing
    t = 3 min  -> Processing
    t = 4 min  -> Processing
    t = 5 min  -> Processing still running

No new poll() received.

Result:

    Kafka removes the consumer
    from the consumer group

    and

    triggers a rebalance.

Partitions previously assigned
to this consumer will be reassigned
to other consumers in the group.


-----------------------------------
## HEARTBEAT VS MAX POLL INTERVAL
-----------------------------------

heartbeat.interval.ms

    Answers:

        "Is the consumer alive?"

max.poll.interval.ms

    Answers:

        "Is the consumer making progress?"

A consumer may be:

    Alive  -> YES
    Sending Heartbeats -> YES

but still be considered unhealthy if:

    poll() is not called within
    max.poll.interval.ms

Result:

    Consumer removed
    Rebalance triggered


